args.canonical_rel_desc: Indicates that the subject is a collection or set that includes the object as one of its members.
args.justification: In all four relations, the subject is the collection 'stages of the butterfly's life cycle' and the object is a specific life stage (egg, caterpillar/larva, pupa, adult). This is a standard collection–member pattern, so a generic predicate 'has_member' is appropriate and reusable beyond just life stages.
args.remark: Ordering information (first, second, third, final) is captured in qualifiers and does not belong in the canonical predicate.

args.justification: Each relation links a collection of life cycle stages to an individual stage as its member. This is a generic collection/set membership family of predicates, well captured by 'collection_membership_relation'.
Collection–member relations are structural associations between entities rather than physical composition or causality. They naturally fall under a broad ASSOCIATION group.

args.canonical_rel_desc: Indicates that the subject is a component, aspect, or subset of the broader whole represented by the object.
args.justification: The relation describes the butterfly life cycle as one of the processes that 'make up' the natural world, which is a classic part–whole semantics. 'is_part_of' is a standard canonical predicate for such relations.
The butterfly life cycle is framed as one of many processes composing the natural world, which fits the general family of part–whole (merological) relations.

The wording 'that make up' indicates that the natural world is composed of such processes, making this a compositional whole–part relationship at an abstract level. This aligns best with the COMPOSITION group.
